post_text: Worth County School System is pleased to announce that they will continue participation in Community Eligibility Provision (CEP) for Free Meal Reimbursement for School Year 2020-2021. Worth County first implemented CEP in School Year 2014-2015. Through CEP a school district, a group of schools or a single school may offer meals at no charge to all students. This eliminates the procedure of distributing and processing meal applications.
shared_text:

Community Eligibility Provision
text:
Worth County School System is pleased to announce that they will continue participation in Community Eligibility Provision (CEP) for Free Meal Reimbursement for School Year 2020-2021. Worth County first implemented CEP in School Year 2014-2015. Through CEP a school district, a group of schools or a single school may offer meals at no charge to all students. This eliminates the procedure of distributing and processing meal applications.

Community Eligibility Provision

post_text: On Tuesday, September 1, 2020, administrators of Worth County High School, the Worth County School District and city and county law enforcement were made aware of an inappropriate social media account. There have been numerous reports about the account, and we ask that the community not continue to notify local agencies so that their staff may fully devote their time to investigating this matter. We always urge students and staff, if you see something, say something, and are grateful for those in our community who reported the account.

Reports of Inappropriate Social Media Account
text:
On Tuesday, September 1, 2020, administrators of Worth County High School, the Worth County School District and city and county law enforcement were made aware of an inappropriate social media account. There have been numerous reports about the account, and we ask that the community not continue to notify local agencies so that their staff may fully devote their time to investigating this matter. We always urge students and staff, if you see something, say something, and are grateful for those in our community who reported the account.

post_text: Welcome, Coach Bass!
shared_text:
Worth County Middle School
July 29 at 1:59 PM ¬∑

Greetings Worth County Middle School RAMily!

I am Charlie Bass and I am elated to serve as a Worth County Middle School Health and Physical Education Teacher, Head Middle School Football Coach, and Tennis Coach. I am a graduate of Albany State University where I received a Bachelor of Science in Health and Physical Recreation. I have previously coached football, wrestling, and baseball. I also have experience teaching grades K-12. I look forward to bringing my educational and work experience to Worth County Middle School.

Go Rams!

Charlie Bass
cbass@worthschools.net

post_text:
2020-2021 school year is still scheduled to start in August. Below is for WCSD employees who are working during the summer and public access.

Worth County Schools will resume full operation of all facilities beginning Tuesday, July 7, 2020. Hours will be 8:00am - 4:00pm. All facilities will have COVID-19 protocols for those entering the facilities, so we ask for everyone's cooperation and patience as we continue to do our best keeping everyone safe. Upon entering the facility you will need to:

Disinfect hands:
Have a temperature screening completed
Sign in and answer multiple questions about possible exposure to COVID-19.
Social distancing of at least 6 feet must be adhered to at all times.
Facilities may require face masks in all common areas; visitors should supply their own face masks.
Waiting areas will be limited to a maximum of 10 persons at a time if space permits.

Due to COVID-19, the district competition was cancelled. Therefore, Georgia 4-H created a virtual 4-H Project Achievement. 84 youth in Southwest Georgia competed in our contest. WCES students who participated were: Shyan Foster, D.J. Easom, Jake Thompson, and Jeffrey Reed.



Shyan Foster received 2nd place in the Paleontology project area.



D.J. received honorable mention in the Team Sports project area.



Jake received 1st place in the Outdoor Survival Skills project area.



Jeffrey received honorable mention in Dog Care and Training project area



Congratulations to these students on a job well done! WCES is proud of you!

In compliance with O.C.G.A. ¬ß 50-18-72(a)(11), the Worth County Board of Education announces three persons who have been determined best qualified for the position of Superintendent of Schools in Worth County. The finalist are Dr. Shannon Norfleet, Principal Thomasville High School, Mr. Shane Miller, Superintendent of Schools in Miller County, and Nehemiah Cummings, Assistant Superintendent, Finance and Federal Programs for the Brantley County School System. Accompanying this release are all of the documents presented to the Worth County School System regarding these three candidates.

The Worth County Board of Education has scheduled a meeting for 7:00 p.m. on May 26, 2020 to select the Superintendent of Schools.
For further information please contact Tommy Coleman at (229) 439-4000.

post_text: Very proud of this WCSD student continuing to give back to her community. #RAMPride Janya!
shared_text:
Phoebe Worth Medical Center
April 30 at 9:21 PM ¬∑

Today we received a special donation of face masks. Janya Green, 4H farm manager of The Village Community Garden, Sylvester GA, donated face masks she made for healthcare workers. Also, in attendance was Rep. Bill Yearta who sponsored the face mask project.

Janya, who is 16 years old and already very active in the community, said she felt a need to do something during these challenging times to help. So, as part of the 4H Village Community Garden she started sewing masks and has posted virtual lessons on the garden's Facebook page to teach others within the community how to sew a face mask.

Thank you Janya and Rep. Bill Yearta for your support and donation!
üíöüíô #maskup #coronavirus

Pictured from left to right: Sam X White, Village Community Garden Founder, Kim Gilman, Phoebe Worth Medical Center CEO, Rep. Bill Yearta and Janya Green, 4H Village Farm Manager.

post_text: Jordan Curry, a Junior at WCHS, was selected by WCHS teachers to have an interview with Mitchell EMC for a spot to attend the Washington Youth Tour. Recently, Jordan traveled to Camilla for the interview and was selected as a delegate to go on the Washington Youth Tour. Only four students out of the Mitchell EMC area were selected for this trip. The Washington Youth Tour is Georgia's oldest leadership program for teens. Mitchell EMC sponsors students for this exciting, educational trip. The week-long tour is jam-packed with sightseeing where history comes to life. While touring, students will visit many of the major monuments and memorials, including the Lincoln Memorial, the Jefferson Memorial, Washington Monument, and the White House. Students will also visit Capitol Hill where they will meet with Georgia‚Äôs senators and congressmen. Many other activities and sights are also included in this week-long adventure. Congratulations to Jordan for being selected for this great opportunity! #WCHS #GoRams #RamPride

post_text:
WCHS's PBIS focus for the month of March is the importance of having a positive attitude. This month, and always, we ask that students remember that a positive attitude enables a person to accomplish goals that others cannot due to a negative attitude. Below are a few key points that teachers and students will focus on this month.

Positive Attitude:

Being positive in any situation allows a person to find solutions rather than create problems.
Always have a positive attitude no matter what the circumstance.
Positive people are the calming force that others look to in times of need.
The opportunity for success is right in front of you. You have to choose success.

WCES is participating in the Compassion Games from February 12th - March 13th. This was a challenge bought to us by APEX (Aspire) as their climate change project. For an entire month, the students earned BLUE RAM BUCKS when caught showing compassion. This can look like simply holding the door open or by paying it forward in the classroom. Students were challenged to say thank you, write a kind note, sit by someone new, etc. Teachers have also assigned class projects to give back to the community. ANYTHING that showed compassion earned a Blue RAM Buck. The BLUE Ram Bucks are cashed in at the school store where students can purchase different items. Top winners also received a prize. Compassion Games was a fun and creative way to ignite and catalyze compassionate action in our school. We hope that our students will continue to spread kindness like confetti! Feel free to contact me via phone 229-776-8605 ext. 1433 or via email: stouze@worthschools.net. Keep working hard, WCES students! Show kindness and compassion!

As of February 24th, here are the totals:

post_text: Students at WCES recently participated in the annual Jump Rope for Heart. Students who donated or raised at least $5 participated in the jump off. All participants were given Ram Bucks for showing compassion by helping out the American Heart Association. Grade level winners were awarded a trophy for their win. The top winners per grade level were: 3rd grade - Tye King, 4th grade - Khody Crutchfield, and 5th grade - Isabelle Hancock. The top fundraiser was also awarded a trophy for their donation and fundraising. This year we had a tie between two students. Noah Devane and Marshall Jones will both receive a trophy for their extraordinary donations. A pizza party was another incentive for the class who raised the most money. Mrs. Rogers' fourth grade class donated over $1000 and will receive a pizza party courtesy of WCES. Way to go, students and parents! WCES is proud of you!

Our WCHS Beta Club members performed extremely well at this year's Georgia State Beta Club Convention. With stiff academic competition from public and private schools across the state, our students usually place in the top five once every five years. This year, WCHS took home four top 4 finishes out of a pool of over 2,000 academically talented competitors. Congratulations to the following state winners who are eligible to compete at the National Convention in Fort Worth, Texas:

David Singletary- 2nd place in Agriscience
Cole Tucker- 3rd place in Social Studies

Olivia Yonce- 4th place in Creative Writing

Awesome job, guys! We are so proud of your hard work! #RamPride

post_text:
Congratulations to our 2020 STAR Student, Gregory Williams! Mr. Williams selected Social Studies teacher, Mr. Josh Miller as the 2020 STAR Teacher.

The Page Student-Teacher Achievement Recognition (STAR) program is sponsored, administered, and promoted by the Professional Association of Georgia Educators (PAGE). Since its creation by the Georgia Chamber of Commerce, the STAR program has honored nearly 27,500 students and the teachers they have selected as having had the most influence on their academic achievement. To obtain the STAR nomination, graduating high school seniors must have the highest score on a single test date on the SAT and be in the top 10 percent or top 10 students of their class based on grade point average. The Sylvester Kiwanis Club is the local STAR program sponsor. This is an outstanding accomplishment, and we are very proud of you both! #RamPride

post_text:
Students in Mr. Cory Miller's Welding classes toured several businesses in Sylvester and Tifton on Tuesday, January 21, 2020. Students toured Park Built and Scales, Systems & Automation in Sylvester. A special thanks to Stacey Roberts and Jimmy Parker for allowing these students to tour their facilities and learn more about the welding industry and other opportunities associated with the welding industry.



Students then traveled to Tifton and toured First Products. Students were allowed to tour the facility and actually watch products being made. First Products ships products all over the United States and other countries as well.



Students completed the day at Southern Regional Technical College. Ms. Mandy Ponder met with the students to explain the admission policy. Then students were given a tour of the different labs on campus. Students toured the Drafting classroom and the Welding Lab. Instructors were on hand to give an overview of the courses taught and answer questions from students.

text:
Students in Mr. Cory Miller's Welding classes toured several businesses in Sylvester and Tifton on Tuesday, January 21, 2020. Students toured Park Built and Scales, Systems & Automation in Sylvester. A special thanks to Stacey Roberts and Jimmy Parker for allowing these students to tour their facilities and learn more about the welding industry and other opportunities associated with the welding industry.



Students then traveled to Tifton and toured First Products. Students were allowed to tour the facility and actually watch products being made. First Products ships products all over the United States and other countries as well.



Students completed the day at Southern Regional Technical College. Ms. Mandy Ponder met with the students to explain the admission policy. Then students were given a tour of the different labs on campus. Students toured the Drafting classroom and the Welding Lab. Instructors were on hand to give an overview of the courses taught and answer questions from students.

WORTHSCHOOLS.NET
WCHS Welding Students Tour Welding Facilities

Six WCHS FBLA students attended the FBLA Region I Conference at Southern Regional Technical College in Moultrie, GA, on Friday, January 17, 2020.

The following students won awards at the conference:
Luke Cooper - 1st place Client Services
Lora Coxwell - 1st place Public Speaking
Kyjuana Vance - 2nd place Impromptu Speaking
Fatima Resendez - 5th place Intro to Public Speaking
Zakkery Parton - 6th place Business Calculations

Congratulations to these students! We are very proud of your hard work! #RamPride

Individual photos can be found by clicking the following link.
FBLA Region I Conference

(Group Picture) Pictured left to right: Fatima Resendez, Ranijel Farley, Lora Coxwell, Madison Patton, Kyjuana Vance, and Luke Cooper (Zakkery Parton not available at the time of the picture.)

post_text: The WC school system is supporting our deployed men and women by wearing red on the 2nd Friday of each month. All proceeds will go toward supporting WCHS students in obtaining valuable life/vocational skills through community-based instruction. The short sleeve and long sleeve shirts say, "Wear red today as we are still at war. Stand for those who keep us safe. Pray for those under attack until all come back safely." The raglan only has a design on the front that says, "Remember Everyone Deployed." If you would like to order a shirt, the last day to order/pay is February 3rd. All order forms and payments can be given to the secretary at Worth County High School. Please contact Mrs. Garwood or Mrs. Tillery at WCHS (229-776-8625)with any questions.

post_text: Congratulations to WCHS Junior, Talley Powell, for earning a spot in the Georgia All-State Band for her flute performance during the second round of auditions on Saturday, January 11, 2020, in McDonough. This is the second year in a row that Talley has qualified for the Georgia All-State Band. She will travel to Athens, Georgia during the week of March 5th to attend this statewide event. Congratulations, Talley, for being one of the top 10 flute players in the state of Georgia! We are so proud of your hard work and dedication! #RamPride

post_text:
WCES Parents: Please take the a few minutes to fill out the Computers for Education booklet that was sent home with your child today. Each booklet contains 11 postcards that needs to be completely filled out in black or blue ink and returned as soon as possible. For every completed booklet that is filled out, WCES will receive $2.25 to purchase headphones and/or other technology for the classroom. There is NO obligation to buy anything. All students who return the booklet completely filled out will receive a free fitness watch. Booklets are due back by January 17th.

As always, thank you for your continued support at WCES!
